<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="365" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,719]" pageId="9" pageNumber="365">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,622,647]" pageId="9" pageNumber="365">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles closely both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1923" box="[732,855,623,647]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Stenotortor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inocarpi">
<emphasis box="[732,855,623,647]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="365">S. inocarpi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[911,1083,623,647]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Stenotortor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subhimalaya">
<emphasis box="[911,1083,623,647]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="365">S. subhimalaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has a more acutely pointed head and the crown is 1.5 times the length of the pronotum, whereas in other Oriental species with similar coloration, the crown is less than 1.4 times as long as the pronotum.
</paragraph>
